        "\n",
        "## Python Fundamentals\n",
        "\n",
        "Now that we have finished our set up we are ready to begin coding in `python`.  We will start with the basics including variable assignment, data types and basic operations.  \n",
        "\n",
        "### `print()` Function\n",
        "\n",
        "As with every introduction to `python` programming, we first introduce the `print()` function which displays the output:"
      ],
      "id": "3566b379"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "print(\"Hello\" + \" \" + \"world!\")"
      ],
      "id": "4e93ba4b",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Variables and Assignment\n",
        "\n",
        "A **variable** is a named container for storing a value.  In Python, we create one by assigning a value with `=`.  Here we create three variables called `name`, `age` and `height`:"
      ],
      "id": "1ee98bf5"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "name = \"Alice\"\n",
        "age = 25\n",
        "height = 5.6\n",
        "\n",
        "print(name, \"is\", age, \"years old and\", height, \"feet tall.\")"
      ],
      "id": "ecf67afe",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "Variable names should be lowercase with underscores for spaces (e.g. `my_variable`) and cannot start with a number (same as `R`).  \n",
        "\n",
        "### Python Data Types\n",
        "\n",
        "Python has several built-in data types.  The most common are:\n",
        "\n",
        "| Type | Example | Description |\n",
        "|------|---------|------------|\n",
        "|`int` | `42`    | Whole numbers |\n",
        "|`float` | `3.14` | Decimal numbers |\n",
        "|`str` | `\"hello\"` | Text (string) |\n",
        "|`bool` | `True/False` | Boolean (true/false) |"
      ],
      "id": "567a2577"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "x = 42           # int\n",
        "pi = 3.14159     # float\n",
        "greeting = \"Hi\"  # str\n",
        "is_fun = True    # bool\n",
        "\n",
        "# Check the type of any variable with type()\n",
        "print(type(x))\n",
        "print(type(pi))\n",
        "print(type(greeting))\n",
        "print(type(is_fun))"
      ],
      "id": "711a32bb",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "You can convert between types (explored further in our lab on data preparation):"
      ],
      "id": "46b1643f"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "number = 7\n",
        "as_float = float(number)\n",
        "as_string = str(number)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(as_float)   # 7.0\n",
        "print(as_string)  # \"7\""
      ],
      "id": "892c7d2f",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#### Strings\n",
        "\n",
        "Strings are sequences of characters.  Python (unlike `R`) has a lot of built-in functionality for handling strings:"
      ],
      "id": "50d72d53"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "s = \"Hello, Python!\"\n",
        "\n",
        "print(len(s))          # Length of the string\n",
        "print(s.upper())       # All uppercase\n",
        "print(s.lower())       # All lowercase\n",
        "print(s.replace(\"Python\", \"World\"))  # Replace a word\n",
        "print(s[0])            # First character: \"H\"\n",
        "print(s[0:5])          # Slice: \"Hello\""
      ],
      "id": "485cbb6c",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "Note that in python some functions are attached directly to a value or variable and called using **dot notation**: `variable.method()`.  These are called **methods** - functions for a specific data type.  For example `upper()` is the method on the string `s`.  This is our first-look at **object-oriented programming**, something that we will explore as we advance in python.\n",
        "\n",
        "The cleanest way to embed variables inside strings are **f-strings** (formatted-strings):"
      ],
      "id": "11b8ab73"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "name = \"Alice\"\n",
        "age = 25\n",
        "\n",
        "message = f\"My name is {name} and I am {age} years old.\"\n",
        "print(message)"
      ],
      "id": "e55d9ecd",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "This is particularly helpful when combined with looping, for example to efficiently generate labels for multiple plots.\n",
        "\n",
        "#### Lists\n",
        "\n",
        "A **list** is an ordered, changeable collection of items.  Lists can hold any data type, even mixed types (in this way they differ to vectors) and as such are very flexible for data storage.  They are created using **square brackets** `[...]` with items separated by commas:"
      ],
      "id": "970d0f31"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "fruits = [\"apple\", \"banana\", \"cherry\"]\n",
        "\n",
        "print(fruits[0])    # First item: \"apple\"\n",
        "print(fruits[-1])   # Last item: \"cherry\"\n",
        "print(len(fruits))  # Number of items: 3\n",
        "\n",
        "# Modifying a list\n",
        "fruits.append(\"mango\")      # Add to end\n",
        "fruits.insert(1, \"grape\")   # Insert at index 1\n",
        "fruits.remove(\"banana\")     # Remove by value\n",
        "\n",
        "print(fruits)"
      ],
      "id": "77917c95",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "To index items from a list numerically we again use **square brackets** (not curly braces `{ }`).  Note that (unlike `R`) python indexes start from 0.  We can index from the end of the list using the minus signs:"
      ],
      "id": "f2e39593"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "print(fruits[0])\n",
        "print(fruits[-1])"
      ],
      "id": "034265ce",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "We can **slice** a list, which means returning all elements before/after a certain point by using `:`:"
      ],
      "id": "13615354"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "numbers = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\n",
        "\n",
        "print(numbers[1:4])   # [1, 2, 3]\n",
        "print(numbers[:3])    # [0, 1, 2]\n",
        "print(numbers[3:])    # [3, 4, 5]\n",
        "print(numbers[::2])   # Every other item: [0, 2, 4]"
      ],
      "id": "61856f81",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#### Dictionaries\n",
        "\n",
        "A **dictionary** stores data as key-value pairs, like a real dictionary where you look up a work (key) to find its definition (value).  These are defined with brackets ${...}$ where key values are strings:"
      ],
      "id": "2404a3cb"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "person = {\n",
        "    \"name\": \"Alice\",\n",
        "    \"age\": 25,\n",
        "    \"city\": \"New York\"\n",
        "}\n",
        "\n",
        "print(person[\"name\"])   # Access by key\n",
        "print(person[\"age\"])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Add or update a key\n",
        "person[\"email\"] = \"alice@example.com\"\n",
        "person[\"age\"] = 26\n",
        "\n",
        "print(person)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Check if a key exists\n",
        "print(\"city\" in person)   # True"
      ],
      "id": "12cb410f",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Basic Math\n",
        "\n",
        "Python supports all standard arithmetic operations:"
      ],
      "id": "30bec74e"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "a = 10\n",
        "b = 3\n",
        "\n",
        "print(a + b)   # Addition:       13\n",
        "print(a - b)   # Subtraction:    7\n",
        "print(a * b)   # Multiplication: 30\n",
        "print(a / b)   # Division:       3.333...\n",
        "print(a // b)  # Floor division: 3  (rounds down)\n",
        "print(a % b)   # Modulo:         1  (remainder)\n",
        "print(a ** b)  # Exponent:       1000"
      ],
      "id": "3b2950ea",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Branching\n",
        "\n",
        "Branching is a fundamental concept in programming that allows you to control the flow of your program based on certain conditions. In Python, you can use `if`, `elif`, and `else` statements to create conditional logic:"
      ],
      "id": "4471e74e"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "temperature = 72\n",
        "\n",
        "if temperature > 90:\n",
        "    print(\"It's very hot outside!\")\n",
        "elif temperature > 65:\n",
        "    print(\"It's a nice day.\")\n",
        "elif temperature > 40:\n",
        "    print(\"It's a bit chilly.\")\n",
        "else:\n",
        "    print(\"It's cold outside!\")"
      ],
      "id": "33397692",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "Note here that unlike `R` branching statements have no parentheses or brackets, it has a much cleaner and more intuitive syntax.  These The branching conditions are logical statements with a single `True/False` output.  Python uses the standard programming syntax for logical operators:\n",
        "\n",
        "| Operator | Meaning |\n",
        "|----------|---------|\n",
        "| `==`     | Equal to |\n",
        "| `!=`     | Not equal to |\n",
        "| `>`      | Greater than |\n",
        "| `<`      | Less than |\n",
        "| `>=`     | Greater than or equal to |\n",
        "| `<=`     | Less than or equal to |"
      ],
      "id": "ef1017f0"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "x = 10\n",
        "print(x == 10)  # True\n",
        "print(x != 5)   # True\n",
        "print(x > 20)   # False"
      ],
      "id": "d1f011cc",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "We note here another divergence from `R` in the existence of `not`, `and` and `or` rather than mathematical symbols.  Python typically reads more like plain English."
      ],
      "id": "81336cfd"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "is_raining = False\n",
        "\n",
        "# Preferred\n",
        "if not is_raining:\n",
        "    print(\"No umbrella needed!\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Also common: checking if a list is empty\n",
        "items = []\n",
        "\n",
        "if not items:\n",
        "    print(\"The list is empty.\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Combining with and / or\n",
        "logged_in = True\n",
        "is_admin = False\n",
        "\n",
        "if logged_in and not is_admin:\n",
        "    print(\"Welcome, regular user!\")"
      ],
      "id": "27e3ba6e",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "Here are a few rules of thumb for when to use `not`:\n",
        "\n",
        "* Use `not x` instead of `x == False`.\n",
        "* Use `not items` instead of `len(items) == 0` to check for empty objects.\n",
        "* Use `not x in my_list` - or better `x not in my_list` - to check for absence.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Iteration\n",
        "\n",
        "A `for` loop iterates over a sequence.  Similar to branching, we see that python looping syntax has no parentheses or braces:"
      ],
      "id": "8ceb985a"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "fruits = [\"apple\", \"banana\", \"cherry\"]\n",
        "\n",
        "for fruit in fruits:\n",
        "    print(fruit)"
      ],
      "id": "16117000",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "Use range() to loop a specific number of times:"
      ],
      "id": "bda40ff2"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "for i in range(5):\n",
        "    print(f\"Step {i}\")"
      ],
      "id": "17e81bac",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "A while loop repeats as long as a condition is true:"
      ],
      "id": "12fcdae2"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "count = 0\n",
        "\n",
        "while count < 5:\n",
        "    print(f\"Count is {count}\")\n",
        "    count += 1\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Done!\")"
      ],
      "id": "f7369aa4",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
