        "### List comprehension\n",
        "\n",
        "In Python, normally you can fill a list with elements using a for loop as seen in the example below."
      ],
      "id": "0263bbc7"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "deletable": false,
        "tags": []
      },
      "source": [
        "squares = []\n",
        "# Add square numbers from 1 to 100 inclusive to the list \"squares\" if they end in the digit \"4\"\n",
        "for i in range(1,101):\n",
        "    if (i**2)%10 == 4:\n",
        "        squares.append(i**2)\n",
        "print(squares)"
      ],
      "id": "6c295ded",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "Alternatively, you can create this same list in a single line of code by moving the for-loop and if-statement inside the loop's creation. This is called a **list comprehension**.\n",
        "\n",
        "The syntax for a list comprehension is this: \\[**value** **for-loop** **condition**\\]\n",
        "* **value** is the value you want to put into the list\n",
        "* **for-loop** is the for-loop that iterates through a list or a range\n",
        "* **condition** is the if-statement that determines if the **value** is allowed to be inserted into the list\n",
        "\n",
        "For more information, you can read [this beginner's tutorial](https://www.pythonforbeginners.com/basics/list-comprehensions-in-python) on list comprehensions"
      ],
      "id": "ce9c8424"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "deletable": false,
        "tags": []
      },
      "source": [
        "# value: i**2\n",
        "# for-loop: for i in range(1,101)\n",
        "# condition: if (i**2)%10 == 4\n",
        "squares_list_comprehension = [i**2 for i in range(1,101) if (i**2)%10 == 4]"
      ],
      "id": "94ddbb28",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Aligning lists with `zip()`\n",
        "\n",
        "If you need to line up 2 or more lists, Python has a built-in function called **zip()**. This allows you to loop through more than one list at a time such that you get values in each list that have the same index in the other lists. This can also be used within for-loops to make them even more powerful."
      ],
      "id": "0181cba6"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "deletable": false,
        "tags": []
      },
      "source": [
        "a = [1,2,3,4]\n",
        "b = [2,3,4,5]\n",
        "# Print a[0]*b[0], a[1]*b[1],...\n",
        "for x, y in zip(a,b):\n",
        "    print(x*y)"
      ],
      "id": "41ec4cf6",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "**Example:**  Write a function `list_sum` that computes **the square** of _each_ value in `list_1`, **the cube** of _each_ value in `list_2`, and returns a list containing the element-wise sum of these results. Assume that `list_1` and `list_2` have the same number of elements. Try to use a list comprehension to write it all on one line.  I have started the function for you below:"
      ],
      "id": "ceade1d4"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# SOLUTION\n",
        "\n",
        "def list_sum(list_1, list_2):\n",
        "    \"\"\"Compute x^2 + y^3 for each x, y in list_1, list_2. \n",
        "    \n",
        "    Assume list_1 and list_2 have the same length.\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    assert len(list_1) == len(list_2), \"both args must have the same number of elements\"\n",
        "    ...\n",
        "\n",
        "    return [x**2 + y**3 for x, y in zip(list_1, list_2)]"
      ],
      "id": "f3518ca9",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "To test this function we define two lists and call the function:"
      ],
      "id": "afc6ea44"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "list_1 = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\n",
        "list_2 = [6, 7, 8, 9, 10]\n",
        "print(list_sum(list_1, list_2))"
      ],
      "id": "22718a03",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## `numpy` Package\n",
        "\n",
        "NumPy (pronounced \"NUM-pie\") is the numerical computing module, which we will be using a lot in this course. Here's a quick recap of NumPy. For more review, read the following materials.\n",
        "\n",
        "- **[NumPy Quick Start Tutorial](https://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy-1.15.4/user/quickstart.html)**\n",
        "- **[Stanford CS231n NumPy Tutorial](https://cs231n.github.io/python-numpy-tutorial/#numpy)**\n",
        "\n",
        "### Arrays\n",
        "\n",
        "The core of NumPy is the **array**. Like Python lists, arrays store data; however, they store data in a more efficient manner. In many cases, this allows for faster computation and data manipulation.\n",
        "\n",
        "Let's use `np.array` to create an array. It takes a sequence, such as a list or range (remember that list elements are included between the square brackets `[` and `]`). \n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:** Create an array `arr` containing the values 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5 (in that order)."
      ],
      "id": "edd55e8f"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "arr = np.array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])"
      ],
      "id": "30aa3102",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "In addition to values in the array, we can access attributes such as array's shape and data type. A full list of attributes can be found [here](https://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy-1.15.0/reference/arrays.ndarray.html#array-attributes).\n",
        "\n",
        "### Indexing\n",
        "\n",
        "NumPy arrays are integer-indexed by position, with the first element indexed as position 0. Elements can be retrieved by enclosing the desired positions in brackets `[]`. "
      ],
      "id": "48f2d91a"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "arr[3]"
      ],
      "id": "073ac851",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "To retrieve consecutive positions, specify the starting index and the ending index separated by `:` -- *e.g.*, `arr[from:to]`. This syntax is non-inclusive of the left endpoint; notice below that the starting index is *not* included in the output."
      ],
      "id": "3ddccdc4"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "arr[2:4]"
      ],
      "id": "91cc4e32",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Attributes\n",
        "\n",
        "NumPy arrays have several attributes that can be retrieved by name using syntax of the form `arr.attr`. Some useful attributes are:\n",
        "\n",
        "* `.shape`, a tuple with the length of each array dimension\n",
        "* `.size`, the length of the first array dimension\n",
        "* `.dtype`, the data type of the entries (float, integer, etc.)"
      ],
      "id": "1a253fcf"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "arr.shape"
      ],
      "id": "7602051b",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "arr.size"
      ],
      "id": "7435a46b",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "arr.dtype"
      ],
      "id": "ded559dd",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "Arrays, unlike Python lists, **cannot store items of different data types**."
      ],
      "id": "ad05934e"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# A regular Python list can store items of different data types\n",
        "[1, '3']"
      ],
      "id": "07b9e165",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Arrays will convert everything to the same data type\n",
        "np.array([1, '3'])"
      ],
      "id": "c064440d",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Another example of array type conversion\n",
        "np.array([5, 8.3])"
      ],
      "id": "c6333d1e",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Operations on arrays\n",
        "\n",
        "Arrays are also useful in performing *vectorized operations*. Given two or more arrays of equal length, arithmetic will perform **element-wise computations** across the arrays. \n",
        "\n",
        "For example, observe the following:"
      ],
      "id": "cea7e1a4"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Python list addition will concatenate the two lists\n",
        "[1, 2, 3] + [4, 5, 6]"
      ],
      "id": "5371ad21",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# NumPy array addition will add them element-wise\n",
        "np.array([1, 2, 3]) + np.array([4, 5, 6])"
      ],
      "id": "d5c90d6a",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "**Example:** Given the array `random_arr`, assign `valid_values` to an array containing all values $x$ of `random_arr` such that $2x^4 > 1$."
      ],
      "id": "803ffe7c"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "# for reproducibility - setting the seed will result in the same random draw each time\n",
        "np.random.seed(67)\n",
        "\n",
        "# draw uniformly random integers between 1 and 60\n",
        "random_arr = np.random.rand(60)\n",
        "\n",
        "# solution\n",
        "valid_values = random_arr[2*random_arr**4 > 1]"
      ],
      "id": "82eee507",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "**Example:** Recreate the `list_sum` function using `numpy` arrays, calling your new function `array_sum`."
      ],
      "id": "f7d74edc"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "def array_sum(array_1, array_2):\n",
        "    return np.array([x**2 + y**3 for x, y in zip(array_1, array_2)])"
      ],
      "id": "92c4456c",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "You might have been told that Python is slow, but array arithmetic is carried out very fast, even for large arrays.\n",
        "\n",
        "For ten numbers, `list_sum` and `array_sum` both take a similar amount of time."
      ],
      "id": "cdf57ec8"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "sample_list_1 = list(range(10))\n",
        "sample_array_1 = np.arange(10)"
      ],
      "id": "bd2e4813",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "%%time\n",
        "list_sum(sample_list_1, sample_list_1)"
      ],
      "id": "06a1d2e3",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "%%time\n",
        "array_sum(sample_array_1, sample_array_1)"
      ],
      "id": "2274ddec",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "The time difference seems negligible for a list/array of size 10; depending on your setup, you may even observe that `list_sum` executes faster than `array_sum`! However, we will commonly be working with much larger datasets:"
      ],
      "id": "b20dc229"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "sample_list_2 = list(range(100000))\n",
        "sample_array_2 = np.arange(100000)"
      ],
      "id": "4eae91fa",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "%%time\n",
        "list_sum(sample_list_2, sample_list_2)\n",
        "; # The semicolon hides the output"
      ],
      "id": "24e47f73",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "%%time\n",
        "array_sum(sample_array_2, sample_array_2)\n",
        ";"
      ],
      "id": "3bb89a1c",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "With the larger dataset, we see that using NumPy results in code that executes over 50 times faster! Throughout this course (and in the real world), you will find that writing efficient code will be important; arrays and vectorized operations are the most common way of making Python programs run quickly.\n",
        "\n",
        "#### A note on `np.arange` and `np.linspace`\n",
        "\n",
        "Usually we use `np.arange` to return an array that steps from `a` to `b` with a fixed step size `s`. While this is fine in some cases, we sometimes prefer to use `np.linspace(a, b, N)`, which divides the interval `[a, b]` into N equally spaced points.\n",
        "\n",
        "`np.arange(start, stop, step)` produces an array with all the numbers starting at `start`, incremented up by `step`, stopping **before** `stop` is reached. For example, the value of `np.arange(1, 6, 2)` is an array with elements 1, 3, and 5 -- it starts at 1 and counts up by 2, then stops before 6. `np.arange(4, 9, 1)` is an array with elements 4, 5, 6, 7, and 8. (It doesn't contain 9 because `np.arange` stops _before_ the stop value is reached.)\n",
        "\n",
        " `np.linspace` always includes **both end points** while `np.arange` will **not** include the second end point `b`. For this reason, especially when we are plotting ranges of values we tend to prefer `np.linspace`.\n",
        "\n",
        "Notice how the following two statements have different parameters but return the same result."
      ],
      "id": "6056460b"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "np.arange(-5, 6, 1.0)"
      ],
      "id": "c2db250b",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "np.linspace(-5, 5, 11)"
      ],
      "id": "e546434a",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Matrices\n",
        "\n",
        "Arrays are not limited to one dimension (i.e. vectors) but can also be used to define **matrices**. For example, we define a $3\\times 3$ matrix `A` and a $3\\times 1$ vector `b` (the right-hand side of a linear system). "
      ],
      "id": "798b2a49"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "A = np.array([[2, 1, 3],\n",
        "              [4, 3, 2],\n",
        "              [1, 2, 2]], dtype=float)\n",
        "              \n",
        "b = np.array([34, 46, 26], dtype=float)"
      ],
      "id": "1382c03d",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "Elementwise multiplication can be performed with `*` as normal and matrix multiplication by `@`:"
      ],
      "id": "9e3fa605"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Computations with matrices\n",
        "print(A*A)  \n",
        "print(A@A)\n",
        "print(A@b)"
      ],
      "id": "1a5fcef5",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "As one final example of just some of the functionality of `numpy` we demonstrate its ability to solve linear systems.  Consider the following system of linear equations:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{aligned}\n",
        "2x + y + 3z & = 34 \\\\\n",
        "4x + 3y + 3z & = 46 \\\\\n",
        "x + 2y + 2z & = 26.\n",
        "\\end{aligned}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "To find solutions $x$, $y$ and $z$ we can use the `np.linalg.solve` function:"
      ],
      "id": "88316798"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "A = np.array([[2, 1, 3],\n",
        "              [4, 3, 2],\n",
        "              [1, 2, 2]], dtype=float)\n",
        "\n",
        "b = np.array([34, 46, 26], dtype=float)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Task 2\n",
        "x = np.linalg.solve(A, b)\n",
        "print(f\"x: {x[0]:.1f}, y: {x[1]:.1f}, z: {x[2]:.1f}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Task 3\n",
        "print(f\"Verification passed: {np.allclose(A @ x, b)}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Bonus\n",
        "x_inv = np.linalg.inv(A) @ b\n",
        "print(f\"Via inverse — x: {x_inv[0]:.1f}, y: {x_inv[1]:.1f}, z: {x_inv[2]:.1f}\")"
      ],
      "id": "aebc7c5b",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
